    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1879</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am much obliged for your kind &amp; courteous note &amp; for the present of your work on Nectaries, which I will read, but cannot do so for some time, as I must first read another book &amp; I get on very slowly with German.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Your book will be particularly useful to me &amp; my son Francis,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> as we have lately observed one little fact about nectaries &amp; which, <hi rend="underline">if it turns out true</hi>, is interesting; but we shall have to wait till next summer.</p>
                    <p>I suppose you have seen M. Bonnier’s strange book. He seems to deny that nectaries ever have been modified to insure or increase the visits of insects!<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With many thanks, I remain | Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 <hi rend="italic">Kent</hi>.] <hi rend="italic">before del with parentheses added</hi> ‘(<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)’ </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10622.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Behrens 1879</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12300.xml">letter from W. J. Behrens, 8 November 1879</ref>.</note> 
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref>.</note>   
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_532.xml">Gaston Bonnier</ref>’s book was on the anatomy and physiology of nectaries (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10531.xml">Bonnier 1879a</ref>); for his view on the modification of nectaries, see <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., pp. 30–3.
                </note>  
        </div> 
     
